				\begin{document}$$i = 1, 2, 3$$\end{document}i=1,2,3, after the middle of September is not sufficient to produce the rapid increase that we actually observe in the real data over a month (from 15/09 to 21/10). Indeed, from the middle and lower panels of Fig. 12 we can notice a barely perceptible increase of the simulated cases (both total and new daily cases) at the end of the considered time interval (indeed, the same number of cases are basically obtained until October 21 without reducing \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
